 the 1820s and 1830s by unearthing the life of one man. Stephanos Vogorides (1780–1859) was part of a network of Christian elites known phanariots, institutionally excluded from power yet intimately bound up with Ottoman governance. By tracing the contours of the wide-ranging networks—crossing ethnic, religious, and institutional boundaries—in which the phanariots moved, Philliou provides a unique view of Ottoman power and, ultimately, of the Ottoman legacies in the Middle East and Balkans today. What emerges is a wide-angled analysis of governance as a lived experience at a moment in which there was no clear blueprint for power.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aPhanariotszTurkeyxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh  a19th century european history.  a19th century global history.  a19th century northern african history.  a19th century western asian history.  achristian elite.  achristianity.  acolonialism.  agreat ottoman empire.  agroundbreaking.  ahistory.  aimperial crisis.  aimperial modernization.  aimperialism.  aistanbul.  alate ottoman empire.  amiddle east.  amilitary.  amodernization.  anationalism.  aottoman empire.  aphanariots.  areform.  areligion.  arevisionist history.  arevolution.  astephanos vogorides.  atanzimat.  athe balkans.  awesternizing reforms.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026633940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094775740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520947757423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520947757/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZD